smell_analysis.justification: No empty diagrams were found; each page labeled as a diagram (package, use-case, activity, class, state, or database) shows named elements or actions (e.g., pages 1-19).

The use case diagrams on pages 2 and 3 list several use cases and actors, but the provided content does not explicitly show any use case oval that is clearly unassociated with all actors; therefore no unambiguous violation is visible.

Across the use case diagrams (pages 2 and 3), the use case names appear to describe distinct activities (e.g., 'Vaata aktiivseid autosid' vs 'Vaata kõiki autosid'; 'Aktiveeri auto' vs 'Muuda auto mittaktiivseks'), and actor associations are not explicitly shown as identical for any near-duplicate pair. No clear same-activity duplicates with the same actor are visible.

On the package-style page 1, the listed subsystems/registers and their items do not visibly show two or more distinct model elements with the same primary name inside the same package. Repeated tool-generated annotations such as '(from Registrid)' and similar are treated as metadata per the rules.

The database diagrams (pages 14-19) show PK/FK structures and standard shared columns; there is no explicit, unambiguous evidence of the same data value being redundantly stored in multiple tables without a foreign key connection. Identically named generic columns are excluded by the rule.

Use case names on pages 2 and 3 appear consistently verb-led in form (e.g., 'Tuvasta kasutaja', 'Vaata aktiivseid autosid', 'Registreeri auto', 'Muuda autot', 'Lõpeta auto', 'Unusta auto'). No inconsistent naming form is clearly visible.

The state diagram on page 9 lists several states (Aktiivne, Mitteaktiivne, Lõpetatud, Ootel, Unustatud) with a start node, but the content provided does not explicitly show any state that is clearly unreachable. Therefore no unambiguous violation is visible.

The activity diagram on page 4 lists actions and decision points, but there is no explicit indication of any action that cannot be reached. Without a clear unreachable path shown in the provided content, this rule is not triggered.

The conceptual class diagrams (pages 5-13) display multiplicities in the text (e.g., '1', '0..*', '0..1'), and the database diagrams (pages 14-19) use standard FK connectors which are exempt even if explicit multiplicity labels are not printed. No UML-style relationship clearly lacking multiplicity at both ends is unambiguously visible.

No single analyzed diagram page clearly shows 10 or more central elements of the counted types. For example, page 2 appears to show 4 use cases, page 3 fewer than 10 use cases, and page 15 shows about 9 classifier tables. Actors and overview elements are excluded from the count.

Although some tables/classes (e.g., 'auto' in the database-focused pages 17-18) list multiple FK-related annotations, the rule requires 6 or more distinct visible drawn relationship lines on that specific diagram. The provided content does not unambiguously show the count of separately drawn lines, so no clear violation is confirmed.
The rule depends on visual spacing distances between related elements. The provided text does not allow an explicit, unambiguous measurement of distances, so no violation can be confirmed.

Use case names on pages 2-3 and visible action names on the activity diagram page 4 appear to start with active verbs (e.g., 'Tuvasta', 'Vaata', 'Registreeri', 'Muuda', 'Lõpeta', 'Otsi', 'Vali'). No clearly non-verb-starting use case/action name is visible.

No class, table, attribute/column, or use case name with 3 or fewer characters is clearly visible. Examples like 'Isik', 'auto', 'Riik', 'Klient', 'Töötaja', 'parool', 'nimetus' exceed this threshold.

A class named 'auto' appears in the conceptual class diagrams (e.g., 'Autode register::auto' on pages 5, 11, and 12). This class name starts with a lowercase letter, which explicitly violates the rule.

Attribute and column names shown in the class and database diagrams appear to start with lowercase letters (e.g., 'eesnimi', 'perenimi', 'isikukood', 'on_aktiivne', 'vin_kood', 'reg_aeg'). No attribute/column name starting with an uppercase letter is clearly visible.

Database table names visible on pages 14-19 appear to be singular or domain-specific compound forms (e.g., 'Isik', 'Kasutajakonto', 'Klient', 'Tootaja', 'Auto_mark', 'Auto_kategooria'). No unambiguous plural table name that should represent a singular domain object is visible.

No class, table, or attribute/column name visibly uses a disallowed type-indicating prefix such as 'tbl_' or 'uc_'. The visible PK_, FK_, pfK_, and IXFK_-style prefixes appear in constraint/index contexts and are explicitly allowed by the rule.
